So everything you make has three properties.

WEIGHT. A real object has mass — you feel it the moment it leaves your hand. An answer has weight when it costs something to be wrong: a specific number, a named tradeoff, a claim that could fail a test. Hollow things float. Before you pass it over, heft it. If it weighs nothing — if every sentence would survive being false — you've made a balloon, not a tool. Put something load-bearing in it.

